      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thank you for ''Behind the Music: Organs Go Electronic'' (July 27) on the use of digitally sampled sounds in hybrid organs. Over the years I have played some pipe organs that left me shuddering. I have also played some electronic-digital instruments that served better.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thank you for ''Behind the Music: Organs Go Electronic'' (July 27) on the use of digitally sampled sounds in hybrid organs. Over the years I have played some pipe organs that left me shuddering. I have also played some electronic-digital instruments that served better.</p>
        <p>A traditional John Pike Mander organ I recently played in Immanuel-on-the-Hill Episcopal Church in Alexandria, Va., is very small by New York City church standards, but it is beautifully balanced and voiced, and the mechanical action is wonderful.</p>
        <p>It doesn't take a large instrument to fill the musical bill. It takes a well designed and executed instrument -- and that may not be so cost-prohibitive as some think.</p>
        <p>JEANNE C. LOWE  Arlington, Va.</p>
      </block>
